al motives driving this assistance. With five case studies from Greece, Tanzania, Pakistan, Uganda, and Egypt, the book tracks refugee self-reliance as a malleable concept used to pursue ulterior interests. It reshapes understandings of refugee self-reliance and delivers important messages for contemporary policy making. The first chapter is available Open Access under CC-BY-NC-ND licence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRefugeesxEconomic conditions. 0aSelf-reliance. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831111967700 cprintz978152921909840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781529219111423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781529219111/original  a978-3-11-119677-0  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles